From da8a5dae9d1958a6399eec734604553891ae1815 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Volker Badziong <development@richtfest.tech>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 16:21:46 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 11/11] Trigger host ramdisk-setup units via systemd D-Bus
 before container create

Phase 0 of the ramdisk-sharing design: Wings does not manage mounts itself and
never will. Instead, Environment.Create() asks systemd to (re)start a named,
pre-existing unit -- the host's own soulmask-pak-ramdisk-setup.sh /
soulmask-static-ramdisk-setup.sh .service units, or any other admin-installed
unit -- and waits for the job to finish before proceeding to convertMounts()/
ContainerCreate(). The unit's own script remains the only thing that ever
touches a mount.

WINGS_CG_RAMDISK_UNITS is a new admin-only, per-server egg/server variable
(comma- or newline-separated unit names, mirroring WINGS_CG_CHILD_SERVERS'
list convention). Every requested name must also appear in the new node-level
docker.allowed_ramdisk_units allowlist or it is rejected and logged, never
acted on -- the same fail-closed pattern docker.allowed_cgroup_parents already
uses for WINGS_CGROUP_PARENT, applied here because a unit name is even more
dangerous to trust blindly: unlike a cgroup slice, an arbitrary systemd unit
could be sshd, a firewall service, or anything else installed on the host.
Unlike the cgroup-parent allowlist there is no built-in fallback namespace --
an empty docker.allowed_ramdisk_units permits triggering no unit at all.

internal/cgroups gains StartUnit, which issues systemd's "start" job
(StartUnitContext) against a persistent unit already defined on disk, and
blocks on the job-done channel exactly like Ensure/Stop already do, bounded by
a new TriggerUnitTimeout (150s: the ramdisk-setup units' own TimeoutStartSec=
120 plus margin). This is deliberately never "restart" (RestartUnitContext):
restarting an already-active oneshot unit runs ExecStop before ExecStart,
which would tear down a live sibling server's bind mount -- confirmed by a
new systemd e2e integration test (TestStartUnitIntegration) that starts a real
oneshot unit twice (proving the second call is a no-op: ExecStart does not
re-run) and then contrasts it against `systemctl restart` on the same unit
(proving restart DOES run ExecStop then ExecStart), using a marker file to
observe exactly which of the unit's ExecStart/ExecStop ran.

Fail-open throughout: a rejected, missing, failing, or slow unit is logged
and never blocks container creation -- a missing ramdisk share degrades to
each server keeping its own private copy, which is safe.

Also factors the comma-or-newline list-splitting logic (previously inlined in
ChildServersFromEnv) into a shared splitCommaOrNewlineList helper, reused by
the new RamdiskUnitsFromEnv.

Tests: unit tests for RamdiskUnitsFromEnv parsing (comma/newline, dedup,
order) and DockerConfiguration.ResolveRamdiskUnits (allowlist accept/reject/
empty-allowlist/mixed-list); docker integration tests proving Create() fails
open when systemd is unreachable and when a requested unit is not allowlisted
(both verified against a real Docker daemon); a systemd e2e integration test
proving the start-vs-restart idempotency contract against a real systemd
instance.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
